Step 1 â€” Create a global defaultValue pipe
This pipe safely replaces any undefined or null value with a fallback (blank, "N/A", etc.), and works across all components.
ğŸ“„ src/app/shared/pipes/default-value.pipe.ts
import { Pipe, PipeTransform, inject } from '@angular/core';
import { DEFAULT_FALLBACK } from './pipe.config';

@Pipe({
  name: 'defaultValue',
  standalone: true,
})
export class DefaultValuePipe implements PipeTransform {
  private globalFallback = inject(DEFAULT_FALLBACK, { optional: true }) ?? '';

  transform(value: any, fallback: string = this.globalFallback): any {
    return value === undefined || value === null ? fallback : value;
  }
}

ğŸ“„ src/app/shared/pipes/pipe.config.ts
import { InjectionToken } from '@angular/core';

export const DEFAULT_FALLBACK = new InjectionToken<string>('DEFAULT_FALLBACK', {
  providedIn: 'root',
  factory: () => '', // global default (can override below)
});

ğŸ“„ src/app/shared/pipes/index.ts
export * from './default-value.pipe';
export * from './pipe.config';


âš™ï¸ Step 2 â€” Register it once in main.ts
This makes it globally available without importing in each component.
ğŸ“„ src/main.ts
import { bootstrapApplication, importProvidersFrom } from '@angular/platform-browser';
import { AppComponent } from './app/app.component';
import { provideRouter } from '@angular/router';
import * as SharedPipes from './app/shared/pipes';

bootstrapApplication(AppComponent, {
  providers: [
    provideRouter([]),
    importProvidersFrom(SharedPipes.DefaultValuePipe),
    { provide: SharedPipes.DEFAULT_FALLBACK, useValue: '--' }, // global fallback
  ],
});

Now every component template can safely do:
{{ user?.name | defaultValue }}
{{ abc | defaultValue:'N/A' }}
{{ email | defaultValue }}

â€¦and youâ€™ll never see undefined, null, or truthy expression warnings.

ğŸ§° Step 3 â€” Make your linter happy
Angular 19â€™s template type checker can flag â€œalways truthyâ€ literal expressions.
If those appear from third-party templates or legacy code, you can suppress globally (not recommended unless needed):
ğŸ“„ angular.json
"angularCompilerOptions": {
  "strictTemplates": true,
  "suppressTemplateTypeChecks": ["alwaysTruth"]
}


âš ï¸ Only use this if you truly must silence those warnings globally; the pipe approach is cleaner.


ğŸš€ Step 4 â€” (Optionally) enforce fallback via global helper
If you prefer to never type the pipe in templates, you can wrap data display in a utility function used in all components:
ğŸ“„ src/app/shared/utils/default.util.ts
export function safe<T>(value: T | null | undefined, fallback: any = ''): T | any {
  return value ?? fallback;
}

Then use in your .ts:
label = safe(this.user?.name, '--');

So even programmatic displays (not just templates) behave consistently.

